				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\upmu $$\end{document}m, respectively) levels is prescribed and limit values are set in accordance with the European Directive 2008/50/EC and similar regulatory acts in other countries. At background sites, ionic and carbonaceous speciation is also prescribed for PM2.5. An example of the worldwide distribution of carbonaceous and other species present in the atmospheric aerosols is reported in Fig. 2.Fig. 2
