				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\upmu $$\end{document}gL-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^{-1}$$\end{document} in several high alpine regions of the Himalayas, Rocky Mountains, Andes, and Alps.

A complete discussion of snow/ice covering reduction falls outside the scope of this review: some results of measurements and models on particular regions and under different perspectives are given in [93–95]. A “rule of thumb” indicates that the average level of the snowline rises by roughly 150 m per Celsius degree [96]: present estimates consider an increase of 0.25 and 0.36 Celsius decade-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
